30 Existing law requires every employer in this State to conspicuously post on the premises
31 where any person is employed a printed abstract, furnished by the Labor Commissioner, of the
32 provisions relating to compensation, wages and hours of employment. (NRS 608.013) Section
33 1 of this bill requires the Labor Commissioner to prepare an abstract of the provisions relating
34 to the employment of children and post the abstract to the Internet website maintained by the
35 Office of Labor Commissioner. Section 1 also requires the Labor Commissioner to include
36 the abstract relating to the employment of children in a two-dimensional bar code, commonly
37 known as a QR code, or other machine-readable bar code used for storing an Internet address,
38 in the abstract relating to compensation, wages and hours of employment that the Labor
39 Commissioner is required to furnish to every employer in this State.
THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF NEVADA, REPRESENTED IN
SENATE AND ASSEMBLY, DO ENACT AS FOLLOWS:
1 Section 1. Chapter 609 of NRS is hereby amended by adding thereto a new
2 section to read as follows:
3 The Labor Commissioner shall:
4 1. Prepare an abstract of this chapter;
5 2. Post the abstract on the Internet website maintained by the Office of
6 Labor Commissioner; and
7 3. Include the abstract in a two-dimensional bar code, commonly known as
8 a QR code, or other machine-readable barcode used for storing an Internet
9 address, in any abstract furnished to an employer pursuant to NRS 608.013.
10 Sec. 2. NRS 609.240 is hereby amended to read as follows:
11 609.240 1. No child under the age of 16 years may be employed, permitted
12 or suffered to work at any gainful occupation, other than employment as a
13 performer in the production of a motion picture or work on a farm, more than [48]
14 40 hours in any 1 week, or more than 8 hours in any 1 day.
15 2. Except as otherwise provided in this subsection and NRS 609.230, no
16 child may be employed, permitted or suffered to work at any gainful occupation,
17 other than employment as a lifeguard, employee of an arcade, stage or theatrical
18 performer or performer in the production of a motion picture or work on a farm,
19 between [10] 11 p.m. and [5] 6 a.m. on any night immediately preceding a school
20 day if the child:
21 (a) Is enrolled in high school [;] at a public or private school;
22 (b) Is 16 years of age or older and under 19 years of age; and
23 (c) Is not declared emancipated pursuant to NRS 129.080 to 129.140,
24 inclusive.
25  A school district or other governing body of the high school or juvenile court
26 may grant an exemption from the restrictions of this subsection if the school
27 district , governing body or juvenile court, as applicable, determines the
28 exemption is in the best interest of the child.
29 3. The presence of a child in any establishment during working hours is prima
30 facie evidence of employment of the child therein.
31 4. As used in this section:
32 (a) “Private school” has the meaning ascribed to it in NRS 394.103.
33 (b) “Public school” has the meaning ascribed to it in NRS 385.007.

